snippet.textDisplay:
Hey matpat! A new Minecraft 1.16 snapshot came out, giving us the new Piglin mob, and amongst other mechanics, one of them got my theorist senses tingling: If a Piglin is brought to the overworld, it quivers and twitches, then turns into a Zombie Pigman(in an animation curiously similar to a Zombie villager being healed). Additionally, they actively avoid Zombie Pigmen in the nether. Why? They fight Wither skeletons voluntarily, but fear an overall weaker mob? The only reason that would be so, is if they avoided conflict out of fear of infection.

This leads to my theory for you to investigate: When the builder civilization was around, Zombies didn't exist, and it was the Zombie virus that destroyed the ancient human civilization.

My working theory is that after the hordes destroyed large quantities of civilization, the survivors did learn to survive and thrive defending themselves, adapting to change as humans are known to do.

But it still failed; they didn't survive, even adapting and overcoming. And I believe that it's because the virus, with enough thousands of pounds of rotting flesh infected, went airborne, and infected any humanoid creatures in the overworld, though villagers seem to have a natural resistance, infection isn't guaranteed, and can be healed.

But the builders, the normal humans, weren't so lucky: those who didn't flee to the end dimension were infected and left their new safe homes to roam the world as zombies.

Now, that leaves steve. As with most diseases, a very tiny percentage of the population are immune, and Steve was one of those, one who survived the hordes and learned to survive on his own.

And so while the nether may be too hot for the virus to go airborne, any Piglins that leave are to the overworld are infected and turned.


I highly recommend that you check out the new Minecraft update snapshots, they are FULL of hidden lore and theory fodder: The warped forest being full pf endermen suggests it was warped by the essence of the End dimension, Soul fire and fossils falling through.
